The ius praetorium, which, as we have already seen, was contrasted by the Roman lawyers with the ius civile, though equally with it a part oi the positive law ol Rome, originated in the ius edicendi possessed

by the higher magistrates The distinction between magistratus maiores and minores was connected with the right to take the

auspices; auspicia maxima might be taken only by consuls and praetors, on whom ‘iustum imperium auspiciumque domi et militiae’ were conferred by a lex curiata. The imperium carried with it also the ius decemendi3 a magistrate invested with imperium had the right ol issuing a decretum, of summoning a citizen (vocatio) to appear before him by his lictors, of ensorcing obedience to his orders by the strong arm of the law. Some oi the magistratus minores, eg. the tribuni

plebis, had the ius prensionis, the right ol arresting persons present ,

belore them and keeping them in detention ; others had 'neither vocatio nor prensio. The praetor, however, who, as has been re· marked, was the supreme judicial magistrate, and who by means of his ius edicendi was enabled to gradually develop a system oi law in which the ius civile was eventually swallowed up, had little oppor- tunity of modifying existing law, still less ol introducing new ruleS, in the earliest period oi his activity. This incapacity arose from the system oi procedure (legis actiones) sanctioned hythe Twelve Tables and somewhat expanded by later legislation; the forms ol actions were rigidly prescribed by statute, and the magistrate had no power to directly alter or extend them; from the forms of actions only could a citizen deduce the rights which were guaranteed him by the civil law. The only mode in which the praetor could enforce a legal principle not contained in that law was by an exercise os his im· perium; he could compel a party to enter into a wager (sponsio) with his advermry, and the fact upon which the wager turned could then be decided in a legis actio.
